Here's a function that takes an array of numbers as input, checks if any of them are prime, and prints them to the console:

```js
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num < 2) return false; // Number less than 2 is not prime
  for (let I = 2; I <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % I === 0) return false; // Number is divisible by some number, not prime
  }
  return true; // Number is not divisible by any number other than 1 and itself, prime
}

function findPrime(arr) {
  for (let I = 0; I < arr.length; i++) {
    if (isPrime(arr[i])) {
      console.log(arr[i]);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage
const nums = [17, 23, 12, 42, 31];
findPrime(nums);
```

The `isPrime` function checks if a number is prime by iterating through all numbers from 2 to the square root of the number. If the number is divisible by any of these numbers, it's not prime. The `findPrime` function iterates through the input array and calls `isPrime` on each number. If the number is prime, it's printed to the console.

